Of all the kinds of music I love, Classical is the only genre I'd call impressive. When Colbert asks a guest if they could listen to only one song for the rest of their lives, I'd pick Beethoven's 5th.

@Bill

I don't know about the US, but in Europe - as I understood it, anyway - for decades a coupe exclusively used to mean a slick and sporty, 2-door car. Some 20 years ago Mercedes started marketing their CLS as a 4-door coupe, and since then more of such cars have appeared on the market. I have always thought it a misuse of the term. If it's got 4 doors it's a sedan (or a limuzyna, as we say in Polish).

I won't comment on the atrocity that is a coupe SUV...

@Jane Wheelaghan

My favourite car nomenclature is the ‘shooting brake’, used to describe an estate car with a more sloping trunk/boot profile and generally more sporty appearance. They still get released now and then, though I’ve seen them called things like sport back and fast back more recently. 

It originates from the days of horse drawn carriages when they were used to transport hunting parties.

@Steve L
Thank you!
And Laurie is a boy's name.

@Jane Wheelaghan

Over here, Laurie is a girl’s name, too. But it once was a boy’s name here as well, as in “Little Women,” but it sounds strange to me. 

Males named Laurence or Lawrence are nicknamed Larry here.

@Joe

